<node id="Matrix">
  <data key="d0">Matrix</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The Matrix is a mathematical structure characterized as a rectangular array of numbers or elements, organized into rows and columns. This construct is used extensively in various fields, including mathematics, computer science, and engineering. Matrices can consist of not just numbers, but also functions or expressions, and are crucial in representing data, particularly in applications like machine learning where they serve to organize input examples.

Each element within a matrix is typically identified by two indices, and matrices are often represented using upper-case bold variable names. The versatility of matrices allows them to be manipulated through various mathematical operations, such as addition, multiplication, and transformations. These operations include specific processes like singular value decomposition and eigenvalue decomposition, which are instrumental in solving systems of equations and analyzing linear transformations.

In summary, the Matrix is a fundamental mathematical construct with widespread applications in organizing data, solving equations, and performing complex operations across diverse disciplines.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0d55b6724597822ab76201288059bd8f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-52465e8bb143dc190c7efa3f3e89fda6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0139bf2dedbbf7d4064d9e8be650befc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d0d3be7ce3dfb930212c12aac0c54ff0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e325d64a50359748cfb47987a361fbb1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1cab33350eba1be65fc00415923198c9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-88935c9c850ad773b6af22d7912a351e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-443f6360d2d3fc61bef3f5a8c109e2f2</data>
