<node id="L1 Norm">
  <data key="d0">L1 Norm</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The L1 Norm is the sum of the absolute values of the elements of a vector, often used in machine learning for its properties relating to sparsity.&lt;SEP&gt;The L1 norm is a mathematical concept used as a substitute for counting the number of non-zero entries in a vector.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0403607cb7181d4a13a232d13fec9630&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e325d64a50359748cfb47987a361fbb1</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1769578881</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="L∞ Norm">
  <data key="d0">L∞ Norm</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The L∞ Norm, also known as the Infinity Norm, measures the maximum absolute value among the elements of a vector.&lt;SEP&gt;The L∞ norm, also known as the infinity norm, measures the maximum absolute value among the elements of a vector.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0403607cb7181d4a13a232d13fec9630&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e325d64a50359748cfb47987a361fbb1</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1769578881</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Frobenius Norm">
  <data key="d0">Frobenius Norm</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The Frobenius norm is a method for measuring the size of a matrix, commonly used in deep learning.&lt;SEP&gt;The Frobenius norm is a measure of matrix size and is computed through the trace of the matrix product involving itself.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0403607cb7181d4a13a232d13fec9630&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-443f6360d2d3fc61bef3f5a8c109e2f2</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1769578881</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Diagonal Matrix">
  <data key="d0">Diagonal Matrix</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A diagonal matrix consists of non-zero entries only along its main diagonal, with all other entries being zero.&lt;SEP&gt;A diagonal matrix is a matrix in which the entries outside the main diagonal are all zero, and its pseudoinverse can be computed by taking the reciprocal of its non-zero elements.&lt;SEP&gt;A diagonal matrix is a matrix where the elements outside the main diagonal are zero, often used in singular value decomposition.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-0403607cb7181d4a13a232d13fec9630&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0139bf2dedbbf7d4064d9e8be650befc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-443f6360d2d3fc61bef3f5a8c109e2f2</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1769578881</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Identity Matrix">
  <data key="d0">Identity Matrix</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The identity matrix is a specific diagonal matrix where all diagonal entries are 1.</data>
